>>LISA: Welcome back.

00:47:23.340 --> 00:47:26.700 align:middle line:84%
My guess is cellular
biologist Dr. Bruce Lipton,

00:47:26.700 --> 00:47:31.080 align:middle line:84%
and we're talking about how our
environment affects our cells.

00:47:31.080 --> 00:47:34.440 align:middle line:84%
But first, I need to ask
you how did your environment

00:47:34.440 --> 00:47:35.700 align:middle line:90%
affect your work?

00:47:35.700 --> 00:47:38.880 align:middle line:84%
I mean, where did you
start with all this passion

00:47:38.880 --> 00:47:42.370 align:middle line:84%
that you have around
epigenetics in your work

00:47:42.370 --> 00:47:43.464 align:middle line:90%
as a cellular biologist?

00:47:43.464 --> 00:47:45.130 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Well,
interestingly enough, it

00:47:45.130 --> 00:47:46.710 align:middle line:84%
started when I was
in second grade,

00:47:46.710 --> 00:47:49.560 align:middle line:90%
so it was a real early kick.

00:47:49.560 --> 00:47:52.630 align:middle line:84%
And basically what happened
was in second grade,

00:47:52.630 --> 00:47:54.885 align:middle line:84%
I remember a science teacher
brought in a microscope

00:47:54.885 --> 00:47:56.790 align:middle line:84%
and that was the
first time any of us

00:47:56.790 --> 00:47:58.080 align:middle line:90%
kids really saw a microscope.

00:47:58.080 --> 00:48:03.540 align:middle line:84%
And inside that microscope
was a slide with amoebas

00:48:03.540 --> 00:48:05.370 align:middle line:84%
and paramecium and
stuff like that.

00:48:05.370 --> 00:48:07.520 align:middle line:84%
Now, you got to realize,
as second graders

00:48:07.520 --> 00:48:09.603 align:middle line:84%
we're just little kids and
everything in the world

00:48:09.603 --> 00:48:10.720 align:middle line:90%
is so big around us.

00:48:10.720 --> 00:48:12.382 align:middle line:84%
And when I had my
chance to stand up

00:48:12.382 --> 00:48:14.840 align:middle line:84%
and I looked in that microscope
and I put my eye down there

00:48:14.840 --> 00:48:17.080 align:middle line:84%
and I finally saw
it, I said [GASPS].

00:48:17.080 --> 00:48:19.650 align:middle line:84%
It was like these little things
were moving around in there

00:48:19.650 --> 00:48:21.149 align:middle line:84%
and there was this
little world that

00:48:21.149 --> 00:48:23.050 align:middle line:84%
was so small you
couldn't even see it.

00:48:23.050 --> 00:48:25.300 align:middle line:84%
And so now I'm a
big guy and those

00:48:25.300 --> 00:48:26.980 align:middle line:90%
are these little tiny things.

00:48:26.980 --> 00:48:30.596 align:middle line:84%
And even in the
mind of my childhood

00:48:30.596 --> 00:48:32.470 align:middle line:84%
at that moment, when I
looked at these cells,

00:48:32.470 --> 00:48:34.800 align:middle line:84%
I realized they weren't
like a pinball bouncing all

00:48:34.800 --> 00:48:36.470 align:middle line:90%
over the place just randomly.

00:48:36.470 --> 00:48:39.180 align:middle line:84%
They moved over here and
looked at something apparently,

00:48:39.180 --> 00:48:41.260 align:middle line:84%
and then moved back and
they looked over here.

00:48:41.260 --> 00:48:43.340 align:middle line:84%
And then they bumped
into each other.

00:48:43.340 --> 00:48:45.500 align:middle line:84%
When they were bumping,
they were communicating.

00:48:45.500 --> 00:48:47.965 align:middle line:84%
And in my child
mind I said, my god,

00:48:47.965 --> 00:48:49.090 align:middle line:90%
they're like little people.

00:48:49.090 --> 00:48:50.660 align:middle line:84%
There's a whole little
world under there

00:48:50.660 --> 00:48:52.060 align:middle line:84%
and they're having
this whole thing.

00:48:52.060 --> 00:48:54.018 align:middle line:84%
And it was really
interesting because from that

00:48:54.018 --> 00:48:58.020 align:middle line:84%
was the very foundation of my
first look into a microscope.

00:48:58.020 --> 00:49:01.640 align:middle line:84%
And then I went through high
school biology and college

00:49:01.640 --> 00:49:03.650 align:middle line:84%
biology major, and
then graduate school.

00:49:03.650 --> 00:49:07.635 align:middle line:84%
And ended up being an
electron microscopist.

00:49:07.635 --> 00:49:12.110 align:middle line:84%
An electron microscopist, the
regular lighted microscope

00:49:12.110 --> 00:49:12.861 align:middle line:90%
you can see cells.

00:49:12.861 --> 00:49:14.526 align:middle line:84%
In the electron
microscope, you get down

00:49:14.526 --> 00:49:16.540 align:middle line:84%
into the molecules that
are making up the cell.

00:49:16.540 --> 00:49:17.160 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:49:17.160 --> 00:49:17.810 align:middle line:90%
Wow.

00:49:17.810 --> 00:49:19.750 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: And it was
the most exciting career

00:49:19.750 --> 00:49:21.590 align:middle line:84%
I could ever imagine
because every day

00:49:21.590 --> 00:49:23.864 align:middle line:84%
when I went to the lab
and turned on the electron

00:49:23.864 --> 00:49:25.530 align:middle line:84%
microscope and started
to look in there,

00:49:25.530 --> 00:49:28.080 align:middle line:84%
it was sort of like the
complete opposite of going out

00:49:28.080 --> 00:49:28.960 align:middle line:90%
into deep space.

00:49:28.960 --> 00:49:30.690 align:middle line:84%
It was like going
into deep space.

00:49:30.690 --> 00:49:31.230 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:49:31.230 --> 00:49:33.180 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: And I would
see things every day

00:49:33.180 --> 00:49:36.430 align:middle line:84%
that no human had ever
seen in the world before.

00:49:36.430 --> 00:49:39.240 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And yet, they
existed inside your body.

00:49:39.240 --> 00:49:40.050 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Exactly.

00:49:40.050 --> 00:49:42.170 align:middle line:90%
And it was like another world.

00:49:42.170 --> 00:49:46.510 align:middle line:84%
And it really brought me back
to the original childhood

00:49:46.510 --> 00:49:49.870 align:middle line:84%
experience that
cells are, indeed,

00:49:49.870 --> 00:49:52.020 align:middle line:90%
miniature living people.

00:49:52.020 --> 00:49:54.400 align:middle line:90%
And a very interesting fact.

00:49:54.400 --> 00:49:56.750 align:middle line:84%
All the functions that we
see in our human body--

00:49:56.750 --> 00:50:00.100 align:middle line:84%
digestive, respiratory
system, excretory, muscle,

00:50:00.100 --> 00:50:02.720 align:middle line:84%
all these things,
even immune system--

00:50:02.720 --> 00:50:05.150 align:middle line:84%
virtually every
single cell organism

00:50:05.150 --> 00:50:07.032 align:middle line:90%
has every one of those systems.

00:50:07.032 --> 00:50:07.990 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Every function?

00:50:07.990 --> 00:50:08.730 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Every function.

00:50:08.730 --> 00:50:11.080 align:middle line:84%
These cells even have an
immune system, digestive,

00:50:11.080 --> 00:50:13.020 align:middle line:84%
respiratory,
reproductive system.

00:50:13.020 --> 00:50:14.820 align:middle line:90%
Cells have a social community.

00:50:14.820 --> 00:50:16.730 align:middle line:90%
Cells exchange ideas.

00:50:16.730 --> 00:50:18.910 align:middle line:90%
Cells create construction.

00:50:18.910 --> 00:50:22.110 align:middle line:84%
So it's just so interesting
that after all those years

00:50:22.110 --> 00:50:24.650 align:middle line:84%
to come back and find my
god, they are little people.

00:50:24.650 --> 00:50:26.240 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Did you
have a relationship

00:50:26.240 --> 00:50:26.950 align:middle line:90%
with these little things?

00:50:26.950 --> 00:50:28.080 align:middle line:84%
You would go there and
you'd get to see now

00:50:28.080 --> 00:50:30.636 align:middle line:84%
what are you doing today and
how are you communicating?

00:50:30.636 --> 00:50:31.760 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: I absolutely did.

00:50:31.760 --> 00:50:34.150 align:middle line:84%
And what was so exciting
is because I would

00:50:34.150 --> 00:50:35.830 align:middle line:84%
put these cells into
a tissue culture--

00:50:35.830 --> 00:50:38.600 align:middle line:84%
I was also doing
cloning stem cells.

00:50:38.600 --> 00:50:42.250 align:middle line:84%
And this was really fun because
I was cloning stem cells back

00:50:42.250 --> 00:50:44.140 align:middle line:90%
in 1967.

00:50:44.140 --> 00:50:46.209 align:middle line:90%
Now that was like 45 years ago.

00:50:46.209 --> 00:50:47.750 align:middle line:84%
A lot of people
think oh, stem cells.

00:50:47.750 --> 00:50:49.230 align:middle line:84%
That's that recent
biology stuff.

00:50:49.230 --> 00:50:49.813 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:50:49.813 --> 00:50:53.637 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: It's like, well, I was
working on them 45 years ago.

00:50:53.637 --> 00:50:55.970 align:middle line:84%
There were only a handful of
us in the entire world that

00:50:55.970 --> 00:50:59.300 align:middle line:84%
had any idea of stem cells
and I was cloning them.

00:50:59.300 --> 00:51:02.150 align:middle line:84%
And what was so neat about
it and this was so cool

00:51:02.150 --> 00:51:05.150 align:middle line:84%
because at some point, as I
was doing these experiments

00:51:05.150 --> 00:51:07.390 align:middle line:84%
with stem cells, I was also
teaching medical students

00:51:07.390 --> 00:51:09.440 align:middle line:84%
about the nature
of how cells work,

00:51:09.440 --> 00:51:12.122 align:middle line:84%
the conventional understanding
that genes control life

00:51:12.122 --> 00:51:13.580 align:middle line:84%
and biochemistry,
blah, blah, blah.

00:51:13.580 --> 00:51:15.170 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's your day job?

00:51:15.170 --> 00:51:16.960 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: That was a day job.

00:51:16.960 --> 00:51:20.340 align:middle line:84%
And yet, I would come in
the lab and these cells

00:51:20.340 --> 00:51:22.590 align:middle line:90%
would show me a world.

00:51:22.590 --> 00:51:24.460 align:middle line:84%
I would look at them
and say, oh, my god,

00:51:24.460 --> 00:51:25.770 align:middle line:90%
what are you guys doing?

00:51:25.770 --> 00:51:28.020 align:middle line:84%
And when I started
to observe them,

00:51:28.020 --> 00:51:29.950 align:middle line:84%
I was completely blown
away because I started

00:51:29.950 --> 00:51:33.210 align:middle line:84%
to realize what I was
teaching in medical school

00:51:33.210 --> 00:51:37.380 align:middle line:84%
was so incorrect in
regard to how cells work

00:51:37.380 --> 00:51:41.290 align:middle line:84%
that, ultimately, I found
that I really couldn't

00:51:41.290 --> 00:51:43.840 align:middle line:84%
in good integrity stay and
teach in the medical school.

00:51:43.840 --> 00:51:44.390 align:middle line:90%
I had tenure.

00:51:44.390 --> 00:51:46.850 align:middle line:84%
I walked out of the
university because I realized

00:51:46.850 --> 00:51:49.051 align:middle line:84%
I am teaching totally
incorrect information.

00:51:49.051 --> 00:51:51.050 align:middle line:84%
Now, of course when I
walked out the university,

00:51:51.050 --> 00:51:53.930 align:middle line:84%
all my colleagues looked at
me, it's like, you're weird.

00:51:53.930 --> 00:51:54.440 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: What's wrong with him.

00:51:54.440 --> 00:51:55.773 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: What's wrong with you?

00:51:55.773 --> 00:51:58.590 align:middle line:84%
And it's like, that stuff is--
you know, that's artifact.

00:51:58.590 --> 00:51:59.760 align:middle line:90%
That's not real.

00:51:59.760 --> 00:52:04.270 align:middle line:84%
Because it so conflicted with
the conventional belief system

00:52:04.270 --> 00:52:07.540 align:middle line:84%
that they sort of just ignored
me and sidelined my work.

00:52:07.540 --> 00:52:10.480 align:middle line:84%
And at some point, I had at
least the fortunate opportunity

00:52:10.480 --> 00:52:14.200 align:middle line:84%
to come back later at Stanford
and redo these experiments

00:52:14.200 --> 00:52:17.250 align:middle line:84%
and then come out with even
more powerful conclusions that

00:52:17.250 --> 00:52:22.110 align:middle line:84%
were absolutely so far ahead
of the conventional academic

00:52:22.110 --> 00:52:23.880 align:middle line:90%
curriculum.

00:52:23.880 --> 00:52:27.220 align:middle line:84%
And so I can sit here today and
say, yeah, in the beginning--

00:52:27.220 --> 00:52:30.160 align:middle line:84%
I love this part--in the
beginning I would tell

00:52:30.160 --> 00:52:32.664 align:middle line:84%
my scientific colleagues
about look at this research

00:52:32.664 --> 00:52:33.580 align:middle line:90%
and the meaning of it.

00:52:33.580 --> 00:52:36.030 align:middle line:84%
And they would look at me
and go, wow, you're so weird,

00:52:36.030 --> 00:52:37.740 align:middle line:90%
that's like you're crazy.

00:52:37.740 --> 00:52:40.650 align:middle line:84%
And it's funny because
if I went to a biologist

00:52:40.650 --> 00:52:43.835 align:middle line:84%
today and actually said this is
what my research was all about

00:52:43.835 --> 00:52:46.210 align:middle line:84%
and this is what it showed,
they would look at me and go,

00:52:46.210 --> 00:52:47.626 align:middle line:84%
so what are you
saying that's new?

00:52:47.626 --> 00:52:48.770 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's new.

00:52:48.770 --> 00:52:51.061 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: So essentially, I
went from freaking them out

00:52:51.061 --> 00:52:51.720 align:middle line:90%
to boring them.

00:52:51.720 --> 00:52:56.460 align:middle line:84%
But the reality is I
saw it a long time ago,

00:52:56.460 --> 00:53:00.041 align:middle line:84%
and it has now become the
main front of the new science.

00:53:00.041 --> 00:53:01.790 align:middle line:84%
And the new science
is called epigenetics.

00:53:01.790 --> 00:53:05.180 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And you have
received awards and changed

00:53:05.180 --> 00:53:07.550 align:middle line:84%
the face of what we
know as the new biology.

00:53:07.550 --> 00:53:08.390 align:middle line:90%
It really is.

00:53:08.390 --> 00:53:10.990 align:middle line:84%
And for people that might
not even know about this yet,

00:53:10.990 --> 00:53:12.615 align:middle line:84%
this is one of the
reasons why I wanted

00:53:12.615 --> 00:53:15.590 align:middle line:84%
you to be on the show is to let
even more people know there is

00:53:15.590 --> 00:53:19.195 align:middle line:84%
a new biology, but it has
a much grander impact.

00:53:19.195 --> 00:53:21.080 align:middle line:84%
That it's not just
about the cells,

00:53:21.080 --> 00:53:22.649 align:middle line:84%
but it has to do
with our evolution.

00:53:22.649 --> 00:53:23.690 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Oh, absolutely.

00:53:23.690 --> 00:53:27.940 align:middle line:84%
And it's so exciting because if
you understand the new science,

00:53:27.940 --> 00:53:30.770 align:middle line:84%
it's so involved with
personal empowerment.

00:53:30.770 --> 00:53:34.530 align:middle line:84%
It personally says you don't
realize how powerful you

00:53:34.530 --> 00:53:37.860 align:middle line:84%
are as a human being
because our limiting beliefs

00:53:37.860 --> 00:53:40.450 align:middle line:84%
that we acquired from
the incorrect science

00:53:40.450 --> 00:53:43.340 align:middle line:84%
prevent us from taking
charge of our own lives.

00:53:43.340 --> 00:53:47.130 align:middle line:84%
And then we see ourselves as
victims of our biology, victims

00:53:47.130 --> 00:53:48.690 align:middle line:90%
of our genes or biochemistry.

00:53:48.690 --> 00:53:50.859 align:middle line:84%
And it turns out, my
god, we're the farthest

00:53:50.859 --> 00:53:51.650 align:middle line:90%
thing from victims.

00:53:51.650 --> 00:53:53.210 align:middle line:90%
We are masters.

00:53:53.210 --> 00:53:57.040 align:middle line:84%
We can control every
aspect of our biology.

00:53:57.040 --> 00:53:59.710 align:middle line:84%
So it's time for people
to gather this power.

00:53:59.710 --> 00:54:00.470 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:54:00.470 --> 00:54:03.120 align:middle line:84%
Because the new civilization
says that we all

00:54:03.120 --> 00:54:06.250 align:middle line:84%
have to know who we really are
so that when we collectively

00:54:06.250 --> 00:54:09.180 align:middle line:84%
work and put our powers
together in harmony,

00:54:09.180 --> 00:54:11.420 align:middle line:84%
the extinction that
seems to be looming

00:54:11.420 --> 00:54:13.602 align:middle line:90%
will actually disappear.

00:54:13.602 --> 00:54:14.560 align:middle line:90%
It will just disappear.

00:54:14.560 --> 00:54:16.770 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Because of how
powerful that we really are.

00:54:16.770 --> 00:54:18.165 align:middle line:90%
Once we realize that, yes.

00:54:18.165 --> 00:54:18.790 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Yeah.

00:54:18.790 --> 00:54:21.770 align:middle line:84%
Because the power that
we've been using right now

00:54:21.770 --> 00:54:24.600 align:middle line:84%
is incorrect, and
therefore, destructive.

00:54:24.600 --> 00:54:28.730 align:middle line:84%
If we turn the tables
and redirect that power,

00:54:28.730 --> 00:54:33.100 align:middle line:84%
then the greatest blossoming
of a garden is available.

00:54:33.100 --> 00:54:34.780 align:middle line:90%
And it's not that far away.

00:54:34.780 --> 00:54:36.030 align:middle line:90%
We can do it almost overnight.

00:54:36.030 --> 00:54:39.145 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I love how you
connect what I speak about

00:54:39.145 --> 00:54:41.770 align:middle line:84%
and what I do in terms
of an interviewer

00:54:41.770 --> 00:54:45.210 align:middle line:84%
on the positive
thinking process.

00:54:45.210 --> 00:54:48.130 align:middle line:84%
But you break it down to the
cellular biology of positive

00:54:48.130 --> 00:54:48.630 align:middle line:90%
though.

00:54:48.630 --> 00:54:51.010 align:middle line:84%
This isn't just rhetoric,
this isn't just affirmations,

00:54:51.010 --> 00:54:52.769 align:middle line:84%
this isn't just a
feel-good conversation.

00:54:52.769 --> 00:54:53.310 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: No.

00:54:53.310 --> 00:54:55.280 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: This is something that
has grounded science to it.

00:54:55.280 --> 00:54:56.050 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Yeah.

00:54:56.050 --> 00:54:57.460 align:middle line:84%
And this is very important
because there's so

00:54:57.460 --> 00:54:59.710 align:middle line:84%
many people who are
distrustful of this concept.

00:54:59.710 --> 00:55:02.175 align:middle line:84%
You say positive thinking,
they go, oh, you new age guy

00:55:02.175 --> 00:55:02.450 align:middle line:90%
and all that.

00:55:02.450 --> 00:55:02.820 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:55:02.820 --> 00:55:04.111 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: And I'm going no, no.

00:55:04.111 --> 00:55:06.080 align:middle line:84%
There's a reason why
positive thinking works

00:55:06.080 --> 00:55:08.510 align:middle line:84%
and there's a reason
why it doesn't work.

00:55:08.510 --> 00:55:12.150 align:middle line:84%
If you understand that, then
you can change the tables

00:55:12.150 --> 00:55:14.520 align:middle line:84%
and not be a victim
anymore, but actually

00:55:14.520 --> 00:55:17.799 align:middle line:84%
turn your positive thinking
into creating a positive life.

00:55:17.799 --> 00:55:19.340 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: OK, so let's
talk about that.

00:55:19.340 --> 00:55:23.555 align:middle line:84%
How exactly are our genes
affected by their environment?

00:55:23.555 --> 00:55:26.890 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: OK, let's go back
to a very simple experiment

00:55:26.890 --> 00:55:29.290 align:middle line:84%
that is so simple that
even if you're not

00:55:29.290 --> 00:55:33.190 align:middle line:84%
a biologist the answer is so
profound you can understand it,

00:55:33.190 --> 00:55:33.699 align:middle line:90%
no question.

00:55:33.699 --> 00:55:34.240 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Good.

00:55:34.240 --> 00:55:37.860 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: OK, so we go
back to let's say 1967,

00:55:37.860 --> 00:55:39.100 align:middle line:90%
and I'm cloning a stem cell.

00:55:39.100 --> 00:55:40.516 align:middle line:84%
You say, well,
what's a stem cell?

00:55:40.516 --> 00:55:43.290 align:middle line:84%
I say well, in truth, a stem
cell is an embryonic cell.

00:55:43.290 --> 00:55:44.513 align:middle line:90%
It's a multi-potential cell.

00:55:44.513 --> 00:55:46.926 align:middle line:90%
It can form bone, skin, muscle.

00:55:46.926 --> 00:55:48.300 align:middle line:84%
It could form any
of the systems.

00:55:48.300 --> 00:55:50.070 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: How do you clone it?

00:55:50.070 --> 00:55:53.340 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Well, actually
you take a piece of tissue.

00:55:53.340 --> 00:55:56.830 align:middle line:84%
You take enzymes to
break the cells apart.

00:55:56.830 --> 00:55:57.331 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:55:57.331 --> 00:55:58.830 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Now you
have a Petri plate

00:55:58.830 --> 00:56:01.320 align:middle line:84%
with lots of different cells
and there are characteristics

00:56:01.320 --> 00:56:04.360 align:middle line:84%
that you can say, oh, that
cell is one of the stem cells.

00:56:04.360 --> 00:56:05.760 align:middle line:84%
There's a physical
characteristic

00:56:05.760 --> 00:56:07.051 align:middle line:90%
of the ones I was working with.

00:56:07.051 --> 00:56:07.950 align:middle line:90%
I say, oh, cool.

00:56:07.950 --> 00:56:10.270 align:middle line:84%
If I put like a
little glass ring

00:56:10.270 --> 00:56:14.580 align:middle line:84%
around that stem cell and
then I put a little enzyme

00:56:14.580 --> 00:56:17.750 align:middle line:84%
in the solution so it
comes off the Petri plate,

00:56:17.750 --> 00:56:20.650 align:middle line:84%
and I take that little
drop with one cell

00:56:20.650 --> 00:56:25.656 align:middle line:84%
and I add that to a Petri
dish and I add one stem cell.

00:56:25.656 --> 00:56:27.030 align:middle line:84%
Now, the significance
is the cell

00:56:27.030 --> 00:56:29.140 align:middle line:90%
divides every 10 to 12 hours.

00:56:29.140 --> 00:56:32.010 align:middle line:84%
And so first there's one,
then there's two, 4, 8, 16,

00:56:32.010 --> 00:56:32.640 align:middle line:90%
et cetera.

00:56:32.640 --> 00:56:34.500 align:middle line:84%
After about two weeks,
I've got thousands

00:56:34.500 --> 00:56:35.650 align:middle line:90%
of cells in the Petri dish.

00:56:35.650 --> 00:56:37.330 align:middle line:90%
Well, that's not the experiment.

00:56:37.330 --> 00:56:39.160 align:middle line:84%
But what it really
shows is this.

00:56:39.160 --> 00:56:42.240 align:middle line:84%
I have thousands of cells, but
here's the most important part.

00:56:42.240 --> 00:56:44.310 align:middle line:84%
They all came from
the same parent.

00:56:44.310 --> 00:56:46.060 align:middle line:84%
So by definition,
I have thousands

00:56:46.060 --> 00:56:48.580 align:middle line:90%
of genetically identical cells.

00:56:48.580 --> 00:56:50.500 align:middle line:84%
Now here's where the
experiment comes from.

00:56:50.500 --> 00:56:53.260 align:middle line:84%
I go to that master
dish with my stem cells

00:56:53.260 --> 00:56:55.350 align:middle line:84%
and I take out
some of the cells.

00:56:55.350 --> 00:56:57.940 align:middle line:84%
And I put them into a
separate Petri dish by itself,

00:56:57.940 --> 00:56:59.600 align:middle line:90%
but I change the environment.

00:56:59.600 --> 00:57:01.230 align:middle line:90%
You say, what's the environment?

00:57:01.230 --> 00:57:03.091 align:middle line:84%
And I say, well,
cells are like fish.

00:57:03.091 --> 00:57:04.340 align:middle line:90%
They live in like an aquarium.

00:57:04.340 --> 00:57:06.920 align:middle line:84%
So you have to put all the
right components in the aquarium

00:57:06.920 --> 00:57:09.750 align:middle line:84%
so they can live and breathe
and eat and live in that world.

00:57:09.750 --> 00:57:11.491 align:middle line:90%
So that's called culture medium.

00:57:11.491 --> 00:57:11.990 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:57:11.990 --> 00:57:13.448 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: So, it's
the environment.

00:57:13.448 --> 00:57:16.110 align:middle line:84%
So I have a chemical composition
of this culture medium.

00:57:16.110 --> 00:57:19.480 align:middle line:84%
I put cells in that dish, so
let's call it Environment A.

00:57:19.480 --> 00:57:21.290 align:middle line:90%
And the cells form muscle.

00:57:21.290 --> 00:57:22.830 align:middle line:90%
I go, that's great, nice.

00:57:22.830 --> 00:57:23.730 align:middle line:90%
I go wait, wait.

00:57:23.730 --> 00:57:26.760 align:middle line:84%
Go back to the original dish
with the original stem cells,

00:57:26.760 --> 00:57:29.500 align:middle line:84%
grab some more
cells and put them

00:57:29.500 --> 00:57:32.590 align:middle line:84%
into yet another dish with
Environment B, a slightly

00:57:32.590 --> 00:57:34.600 align:middle line:90%
different culture environment.

00:57:34.600 --> 00:57:37.790 align:middle line:84%
And in this environment,
the cells form bone.

00:57:37.790 --> 00:57:41.036 align:middle line:84%
And then the last step, I go
back to the original dish,

00:57:41.036 --> 00:57:42.910 align:middle line:84%
get some more cells out
of the original dish.

00:57:42.910 --> 00:57:44.510 align:middle line:84%
Put them in a third
Petri dish yet

00:57:44.510 --> 00:57:46.550 align:middle line:84%
with a different
Environment C. And when

00:57:46.550 --> 00:57:48.440 align:middle line:90%
I do that, they form fat cells.

00:57:48.440 --> 00:57:48.950 align:middle line:90%
Now--

00:57:48.950 --> 00:57:50.630 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Now what are you doing
to change the environment?

00:57:50.630 --> 00:57:51.890 align:middle line:84%
You're just changing
the enzymatic structure?

00:57:51.890 --> 00:57:53.010 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Changing
the composition

00:57:53.010 --> 00:57:53.920 align:middle line:90%
of the growth medium.

00:57:53.920 --> 00:57:54.711 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK, got it.

00:57:54.711 --> 00:57:56.300 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Just the chemistry.

00:57:56.300 --> 00:57:59.180 align:middle line:84%
And so now I come back
and I say, well, look.

00:57:59.180 --> 00:58:02.130 align:middle line:84%
What controls the
fate of the cells?

00:58:02.130 --> 00:58:04.150 align:middle line:84%
Our convention, and what
I was teaching is genes

00:58:04.150 --> 00:58:05.400 align:middle line:90%
control the fate of the cells.

00:58:05.400 --> 00:58:07.440 align:middle line:84%
And I say, well, first
of all, all these cells

00:58:07.440 --> 00:58:09.780 align:middle line:84%
are genetically identical
so you can't tell me

00:58:09.780 --> 00:58:11.585 align:middle line:84%
because it forms
muscle in one dish

00:58:11.585 --> 00:58:15.004 align:middle line:84%
and bone and fat in
another dish that the genes

00:58:15.004 --> 00:58:16.920 align:middle line:84%
did that because they
all have the same genes.

00:58:16.920 --> 00:58:18.410 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Because when you
put them in a different dish

00:58:18.410 --> 00:58:20.460 align:middle line:84%
when you kept the environment
the same, they would replicate.

00:58:20.460 --> 00:58:21.460 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Exactly the same.

00:58:21.460 --> 00:58:22.010 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Exactly the same.

00:58:22.010 --> 00:58:23.200 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: But if I
change the environment,

00:58:23.200 --> 00:58:24.550 align:middle line:84%
they would become
something different.

00:58:24.550 --> 00:58:25.100 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:58:25.100 --> 00:58:26.970 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: So then you're left--
even if you don't know biology,

00:58:26.970 --> 00:58:28.470 align:middle line:84%
I say, well, what controls
the fate of the cell?

00:58:28.470 --> 00:58:30.450 align:middle line:84%
And the answer was
obviously the genes

00:58:30.450 --> 00:58:32.260 align:middle line:84%
were all the same so
it wasn't the genes.

00:58:32.260 --> 00:58:35.160 align:middle line:84%
I say, it was the conditions
or the composition

00:58:35.160 --> 00:58:36.500 align:middle line:90%
of the environment.

00:58:36.500 --> 00:58:38.390 align:middle line:84%
And therefore in
different environments,

00:58:38.390 --> 00:58:40.910 align:middle line:90%
the cells have different fate.

00:58:40.910 --> 00:58:43.610 align:middle line:84%
Now here's an exciting piece
of information and look at it

00:58:43.610 --> 00:58:44.650 align:middle line:90%
this way.

00:58:44.650 --> 00:58:47.130 align:middle line:84%
I have a plastic dish
of cells and I have

00:58:47.130 --> 00:58:48.812 align:middle line:84%
what I call a
healthy environment.

00:58:48.812 --> 00:58:51.020 align:middle line:84%
You know, a nice balanced
environment culture medium.

00:58:51.020 --> 00:58:51.390 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:58:51.390 --> 00:58:53.223 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: And I take
this dish and I move it

00:58:53.223 --> 00:58:55.250 align:middle line:84%
to a less than optimum
environment, not

00:58:55.250 --> 00:58:56.410 align:middle line:90%
a good environment.

00:58:56.410 --> 00:58:58.500 align:middle line:84%
The cells will
start to get sick.

00:58:58.500 --> 00:59:01.560 align:middle line:84%
And if I had a conventional
allopathic doctor

00:59:01.560 --> 00:59:04.300 align:middle line:84%
look at my cells, he'd say,
Bruce, your cells are sick.

00:59:04.300 --> 00:59:06.390 align:middle line:90%
You should give them some drugs.

00:59:06.390 --> 00:59:09.260 align:middle line:90%
And I go, absolutely not.

00:59:09.260 --> 00:59:11.570 align:middle line:84%
All you have to do
is take the cells

00:59:11.570 --> 00:59:14.380 align:middle line:84%
from the less than optimum
environment, put it back

00:59:14.380 --> 00:59:17.910 align:middle line:84%
into the good environment,
the cells will instantaneously

00:59:17.910 --> 00:59:21.170 align:middle line:84%
recover their health and
the cultures will flourish.

00:59:21.170 --> 00:59:22.430 align:middle line:90%
The point is this.

00:59:22.430 --> 00:59:25.410 align:middle line:84%
The cells and their
genetic expression

00:59:25.410 --> 00:59:28.200 align:middle line:84%
become a complement
to the environment.

00:59:28.200 --> 00:59:29.710 align:middle line:90%
And when you are not healthy--

00:59:29.710 --> 00:59:30.440 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:59:30.440 --> 00:59:32.920 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: -then you're
really just reflecting

00:59:32.920 --> 00:59:35.160 align:middle line:84%
that you're not in harmony
or your environment

00:59:35.160 --> 00:59:36.400 align:middle line:90%
is not supportive.

00:59:36.400 --> 00:59:39.320 align:middle line:84%
Let's-- one caveat so we
don't go way off track.

00:59:39.320 --> 00:59:40.190 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:59:40.190 --> 00:59:42.870 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: You can have gene
defects that can cause illness.

00:59:42.870 --> 00:59:43.920 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK, yes.

00:59:43.920 --> 00:59:45.090 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: These are
called birth defects.

00:59:45.090 --> 00:59:47.310 align:middle line:84%
You were born with genes that
were altered in such a way

00:59:47.310 --> 00:59:48.080 align:middle line:90%
that they're not giving you--

00:59:48.080 --> 00:59:49.871 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And what is
the percentage of that?

00:59:49.871 --> 00:59:50.920 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Less than 5%.

00:59:50.920 --> 00:59:51.480 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:59:51.480 --> 00:59:52.730 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: What does that mean?

00:59:52.730 --> 00:59:55.730 align:middle line:84%
95% of the people on
this planet came here

00:59:55.730 --> 00:59:57.930 align:middle line:84%
with a set of genes
that should offer them

00:59:57.930 --> 01:00:01.610 align:middle line:84%
a healthy, happy, harmonious
existence on this planet.

01:00:01.610 --> 01:00:04.070 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But within that set of
genes are the cancer gene is

01:00:04.070 --> 01:00:06.407 align:middle line:84%
present, and maybe the
diabetic gene, and maybe the--

01:00:06.407 --> 01:00:08.240 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Ah, but you
see, this is the fact.

01:00:08.240 --> 01:00:12.130 align:middle line:84%
Is it a diabetic gene or
a diabetic environment?

01:00:12.130 --> 01:00:15.460 align:middle line:84%
Is it a cancer gene or a
cancer causing environment?

01:00:15.460 --> 01:00:17.630 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yeah, so we
have these genes that

01:00:17.630 --> 01:00:19.285 align:middle line:84%
may be present
from our genetics.

01:00:19.285 --> 01:00:19.910 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Yeah.

01:00:19.910 --> 01:00:22.080 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: However, you put it
into a stressful environment

01:00:22.080 --> 01:00:24.505 align:middle line:84%
and it expresses the gene and
activates the gene, right?

01:00:24.505 --> 01:00:25.171 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Right.

01:00:25.171 --> 01:00:27.595 align:middle line:84%
So for example, let's say
you have a particular cancer

01:00:27.595 --> 01:00:29.970 align:middle line:84%
and you go to the doctor and
the doctor says, oh, my god,

01:00:29.970 --> 01:00:32.330 align:middle line:84%
you have this particular
cancer going on.

01:00:32.330 --> 01:00:33.200 align:middle line:90%
And then I say, OK.

01:00:33.200 --> 01:00:36.110 align:middle line:84%
Well, first of all they
will say you have this gene.

01:00:36.110 --> 01:00:39.790 align:middle line:84%
I say, OK, first how many people
with this gene get the cancer?

01:00:39.790 --> 01:00:42.040 align:middle line:84%
And they say, OK, in
this particular gene

01:00:42.040 --> 01:00:45.920 align:middle line:84%
67% of the people that
have this gene get cancer.

01:00:45.920 --> 01:00:47.430 align:middle line:84%
And everybody
starts to freak out

01:00:47.430 --> 01:00:48.960 align:middle line:90%
because that's more than 1%.

01:00:48.960 --> 01:00:49.970 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

01:00:49.970 --> 01:00:50.970 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: And everybody
is like either--

01:00:50.970 --> 01:00:51.270 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: There's a number there.

01:00:51.270 --> 01:00:52.230 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: -focused on
that and I go, yeah,

01:00:52.230 --> 01:00:55.060 align:middle line:84%
but you're not asking the
more important question.

01:00:55.060 --> 01:00:57.530 align:middle line:84%
Apparently 33% of the
people with this gene

01:00:57.530 --> 01:01:00.370 align:middle line:84%
don't have the cancer and
they have the same gene.

01:01:00.370 --> 01:01:02.200 align:middle line:84%
So is it the gene that
causes the cancer?

01:01:02.200 --> 01:01:03.360 align:middle line:90%
And the answer is no.

01:01:03.360 --> 01:01:06.200 align:middle line:84%
Because you can have the
gene and not have the cancer.

01:01:06.200 --> 01:01:09.360 align:middle line:84%
So the question is,
it's not just the gene;

01:01:09.360 --> 01:01:12.110 align:middle line:84%
it's the response
to the environment,

01:01:12.110 --> 01:01:13.980 align:middle line:84%
and this is part of
this new science.

01:01:13.980 --> 01:01:18.360 align:middle line:84%
So my effort was, well, how
does the environmental signal

01:01:18.360 --> 01:01:19.130 align:middle line:90%
control the genes?

01:01:19.130 --> 01:01:20.379 align:middle line:90%
Well, the first thing is this.

01:01:20.379 --> 01:01:21.850 align:middle line:90%
The control is not in the genes.

01:01:21.850 --> 01:01:23.030 align:middle line:90%
That's a given.

01:01:23.030 --> 01:01:25.540 align:middle line:84%
And I started to recognize
that the organism reads

01:01:25.540 --> 01:01:29.620 align:middle line:84%
the environmental information
and then adjusts the genes

01:01:29.620 --> 01:01:33.590 align:middle line:84%
to balance itself against
that particular environment.

01:01:33.590 --> 01:01:35.940 align:middle line:84%
So if you're in an
unhealthy environment,

01:01:35.940 --> 01:01:39.310 align:middle line:84%
you will select gene activity
that's not a healthy gene

01:01:39.310 --> 01:01:40.960 align:middle line:84%
activity but one
that complements

01:01:40.960 --> 01:01:42.124 align:middle line:90%
the unhealthy environment.

01:01:42.124 --> 01:01:43.540 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Stressful
environment, OK.

01:01:43.540 --> 01:01:45.373 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: And if you
really want to recover,

01:01:45.373 --> 01:01:46.985 align:middle line:84%
you don't have to
change the genes,

01:01:46.985 --> 01:01:50.310 align:middle line:84%
the genes change when you
change the environment.

01:01:50.310 --> 01:01:53.215 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's such an-- that is--
I can understand why this was

01:01:53.215 --> 01:01:55.114 align:middle line:84%
an exciting fact
for you to discover

01:01:55.114 --> 01:01:57.030 align:middle line:84%
and I can understand why
you stopped teaching.

01:01:57.030 --> 01:01:58.730 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Well, there I am
teaching medical students

01:01:58.730 --> 01:02:00.760 align:middle line:84%
genes control your life,
and then I walk into the lab

01:02:00.760 --> 01:02:02.200 align:middle line:84%
and the cells are
saying, yeah, right.

01:02:02.200 --> 01:02:03.760 align:middle line:84%
Look, change the
environment and you

01:02:03.760 --> 01:02:05.390 align:middle line:90%
change the genetic activity.

01:02:05.390 --> 01:02:10.920 align:middle line:84%
So that was presaging the
concept called epigenetics.

01:02:10.920 --> 01:02:15.120 align:middle line:84%
Epigenetics as a science was
officially named in 1995.

01:02:15.120 --> 01:02:19.610 align:middle line:84%
I saw the action and the
mechanics of it in 1967.

01:02:19.610 --> 01:02:20.610 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, my goodness.

01:02:20.610 --> 01:02:21.120 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

01:02:21.120 --> 01:02:23.790 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: So really, it was
so far ahead of the game,

01:02:23.790 --> 01:02:26.440 align:middle line:84%
so when I started reporting
it to my colleagues,

01:02:26.440 --> 01:02:27.634 align:middle line:90%
they were not at that level.

01:02:27.634 --> 01:02:28.800 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Accepting it, right.

01:02:28.800 --> 01:02:31.091 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: And therefore, they
looked at it as like, oh,

01:02:31.091 --> 01:02:33.110 align:middle line:84%
that's interesting
but it's not real.

01:02:33.110 --> 01:02:35.610 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: OK, so this is all great
for a Petri dish and cells,

01:02:35.610 --> 01:02:39.150 align:middle line:84%
but how does this relate to us
as walking around human beings?

01:02:39.150 --> 01:02:41.400 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Well, the very
interesting parallel is this.

01:02:41.400 --> 01:02:43.150 align:middle line:84%
When we look in a
mirror and see ourselves

01:02:43.150 --> 01:02:47.340 align:middle line:84%
as individual entities, a
human, I'm Bruce, you're Lisa,

01:02:47.340 --> 01:02:50.320 align:middle line:84%
I say that's a misperception
because we're not

01:02:50.320 --> 01:02:51.460 align:middle line:90%
single entities.

01:02:51.460 --> 01:02:55.400 align:middle line:84%
By truth, we are actually
about 50 trillion cells

01:02:55.400 --> 01:02:57.590 align:middle line:84%
living in harmony
in a community.

01:02:57.590 --> 01:02:59.970 align:middle line:84%
So when you look at yourself,
it's not a single entity.

01:02:59.970 --> 01:03:02.080 align:middle line:84%
It's a community of
50 trillion cells.

01:03:02.080 --> 01:03:04.420 align:middle line:84%
Well, the interesting
correlation is this.

01:03:04.420 --> 01:03:07.070 align:middle line:84%
We are essentially
skin-covered Petri dishes

01:03:07.070 --> 01:03:09.660 align:middle line:90%
with 50 trillion cells inside.

01:03:09.660 --> 01:03:12.750 align:middle line:84%
And there's a culture medium
in there as well called blood.

01:03:12.750 --> 01:03:16.710 align:middle line:84%
So the parallels, if I
change the culture medium

01:03:16.710 --> 01:03:19.500 align:middle line:84%
to cells in a plastic
dish is no different

01:03:19.500 --> 01:03:22.650 align:middle line:84%
if I alter the culture medium
to cells in a skin-covered Petri

01:03:22.650 --> 01:03:23.250 align:middle line:90%
dish.

01:03:23.250 --> 01:03:26.540 align:middle line:84%
So as I said, take a plastic
dish from a good environment

01:03:26.540 --> 01:03:28.360 align:middle line:84%
in a bad environment,
the cells get sick.

01:03:28.360 --> 01:03:30.697 align:middle line:84%
Take a human
skin-covered Petri dish

01:03:30.697 --> 01:03:32.530 align:middle line:84%
from a good environment
to a bad environment

01:03:32.530 --> 01:03:34.129 align:middle line:90%
and the cells will get sick, OK?

01:03:34.129 --> 01:03:34.920 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Same thing.

01:03:34.920 --> 01:03:36.860 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Exact same thing, so
it doesn't make a difference

01:03:36.860 --> 01:03:38.720 align:middle line:84%
if the cells are
in plastic or skin.

01:03:38.720 --> 01:03:39.780 align:middle line:90%
So now here's the issue.

01:03:39.780 --> 01:03:42.544 align:middle line:84%
So we find out from the study
the culture medium controls

01:03:42.544 --> 01:03:43.460 align:middle line:90%
the fate of the cells.

01:03:43.460 --> 01:03:45.126 align:middle line:84%
Then I say, yeah, but
the culture medium

01:03:45.126 --> 01:03:47.360 align:middle line:84%
in my skin-covered
dish is called blood.

01:03:47.360 --> 01:03:50.001 align:middle line:84%
So the question is,
well, then, how or what

01:03:50.001 --> 01:03:52.250 align:middle line:84%
controls the composition of
the culture medium because

01:03:52.250 --> 01:03:54.080 align:middle line:84%
in the end, that
composition is going

01:03:54.080 --> 01:03:55.420 align:middle line:90%
to affect the fate of the cells.

01:03:55.420 --> 01:03:57.670 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So how does our
environment control our blood?

01:03:57.670 --> 01:03:58.300 align:middle line:90%
Is that what you said?

01:03:58.300 --> 01:03:59.575 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Yeah, the
chemistry of the blood,

01:03:59.575 --> 01:04:00.574 align:middle line:90%
which is culture medium.

01:04:00.574 --> 01:04:03.370 align:middle line:84%
So I say, OK, so we
look at the environment

01:04:03.370 --> 01:04:04.929 align:middle line:84%
and we have signals
on the outside,

01:04:04.929 --> 01:04:06.970 align:middle line:84%
we also have signals on
our internal environment.

01:04:06.970 --> 01:04:09.060 align:middle line:84%
I say, yeah, but what
reads the signals?

01:04:09.060 --> 01:04:11.540 align:middle line:84%
And I say, the nervous
system reads the signals.

01:04:11.540 --> 01:04:14.340 align:middle line:84%
The nervous system provides
what we call perception.

01:04:14.340 --> 01:04:16.970 align:middle line:84%
My eyes perceive
light, et cetera,

01:04:16.970 --> 01:04:18.490 align:middle line:90%
and so we have perception.

01:04:18.490 --> 01:04:22.060 align:middle line:84%
So the organism, being
us humans in this case,

01:04:22.060 --> 01:04:24.660 align:middle line:84%
perceive the environment
through the nervous system.

01:04:24.660 --> 01:04:27.230 align:middle line:84%
But there's now one other
step when it comes to humans

01:04:27.230 --> 01:04:30.510 align:middle line:84%
and that is the perception
is not just direct,

01:04:30.510 --> 01:04:31.990 align:middle line:84%
but it's associated
with the mind

01:04:31.990 --> 01:04:34.670 align:middle line:84%
because we interpret
what we see.

01:04:34.670 --> 01:04:37.800 align:middle line:84%
So a perception of the
environment comes in,

01:04:37.800 --> 01:04:40.480 align:middle line:84%
we make an interpretation
called the mind.

01:04:40.480 --> 01:04:45.060 align:middle line:84%
And then the mind feeds back
to the brain and in regard

01:04:45.060 --> 01:04:48.290 align:middle line:84%
to the interpretation
of that perception,

01:04:48.290 --> 01:04:52.040 align:middle line:84%
the brain releases different
chemistry into the blood

01:04:52.040 --> 01:04:54.200 align:middle line:84%
and that goes around
to all the cells.

01:04:54.200 --> 01:04:59.250 align:middle line:84%
Or the signals can go from
the nervous system via nerves

01:04:59.250 --> 01:05:01.920 align:middle line:84%
and directly give the
signals to the cells.

01:05:01.920 --> 01:05:03.490 align:middle line:90%
And the simple point is this.

01:05:03.490 --> 01:05:06.640 align:middle line:84%
The cells, their behavior,
and their genetics

01:05:06.640 --> 01:05:08.870 align:middle line:90%
are affected by the signals.

01:05:08.870 --> 01:05:11.880 align:middle line:84%
But the signals are
mediated by the brain, which

01:05:11.880 --> 01:05:15.310 align:middle line:84%
are in turn controlled
by our mind.

01:05:15.310 --> 01:05:19.840 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So the mind has
the perception of something

01:05:19.840 --> 01:05:21.990 align:middle line:84%
and then feeds
that to the cells.

01:05:21.990 --> 01:05:25.390 align:middle line:84%
So you could be in, say,
maybe a stressful environment,

01:05:25.390 --> 01:05:28.230 align:middle line:84%
but your perception
of that stress

01:05:28.230 --> 01:05:31.530 align:middle line:84%
is what directly relates to
the environment of the body.

01:05:31.530 --> 01:05:32.862 align:middle line:90%
That inner Petri dish, right?

01:05:32.862 --> 01:05:35.070 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Yeah, it's actually
more the interpretation

01:05:35.070 --> 01:05:35.861 align:middle line:90%
of that perception.

01:05:35.861 --> 01:05:37.770 align:middle line:84%
So I give an example
about the difference

01:05:37.770 --> 01:05:40.180 align:middle line:84%
between interpretation
and perception.

01:05:40.180 --> 01:05:43.840 align:middle line:84%
I love extremely hot food,
like with jalapeno peppers.

01:05:43.840 --> 01:05:46.130 align:middle line:84%
If I'm sweating
and eating a meal,

01:05:46.130 --> 01:05:48.760 align:middle line:84%
that means I'm having
a good time, OK?

01:05:48.760 --> 01:05:50.370 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's terrifying to me.

01:05:50.370 --> 01:05:52.411 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Well, see that's
the interesting thing.

01:05:52.411 --> 01:05:54.010 align:middle line:84%
I eat the jalapeno
pepper, and I have

01:05:54.010 --> 01:05:55.640 align:middle line:90%
a perception of jalapeno pepper.

01:05:55.640 --> 01:05:58.170 align:middle line:84%
You eat a jalapeno pepper,
you have a perception.

01:05:58.170 --> 01:05:58.800 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Pain.

01:05:58.800 --> 01:05:59.841 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Pain, well, no.

01:05:59.841 --> 01:06:02.120 align:middle line:90%
But there's an interpretation.

01:06:02.120 --> 01:06:04.480 align:middle line:84%
You see, so we both
ate the same pepper.

01:06:04.480 --> 01:06:07.280 align:middle line:84%
The nervous system picked
up the same information.

01:06:07.280 --> 01:06:10.970 align:middle line:84%
But when you feel
that in your body,

01:06:10.970 --> 01:06:14.071 align:middle line:84%
your mind interprets that as
like, oh, my god, stressful.

01:06:14.071 --> 01:06:14.570 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

01:06:14.570 --> 01:06:17.840 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: When I have the
same chemistry in my body,

01:06:17.840 --> 01:06:21.000 align:middle line:84%
my interpretation of that
is, oh, that's really great.

01:06:21.000 --> 01:06:22.450 align:middle line:90%
So what's the difference?

01:06:22.450 --> 01:06:25.349 align:middle line:84%
It's not the perception, it's
basically the interpretation.

01:06:25.349 --> 01:06:26.640 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: My husband's like that.

01:06:26.640 --> 01:06:28.920 align:middle line:84%
He pours hot sauce on
everything that I make.

01:06:28.920 --> 01:06:29.920 align:middle line:90%
I think it's my cooking.

01:06:29.920 --> 01:06:31.590 align:middle line:84%
But the bottom line
is that yes, it's

01:06:31.590 --> 01:06:33.570 align:middle line:84%
my perception of
the jalapeno pepper.

01:06:33.570 --> 01:06:34.150 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: It's your
interpretation.

01:06:34.150 --> 01:06:35.510 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: My interpretation of it.

01:06:35.510 --> 01:06:39.790 align:middle line:84%
OK, so you travel around
the world, the globe,

01:06:39.790 --> 01:06:42.850 align:middle line:84%
multi continents, you're
all over the planet.

01:06:42.850 --> 01:06:46.340 align:middle line:84%
So how is it that you do not
perceive that as stressful,

01:06:46.340 --> 01:06:49.040 align:middle line:90%
whereas somebody else could?

01:06:49.040 --> 01:06:51.950 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Because the idea
is-- the perception is,

01:06:51.950 --> 01:06:54.150 align:middle line:84%
OK, I'm going to sit in
the same stupid airplane

01:06:54.150 --> 01:06:56.830 align:middle line:84%
in the same stupid airport and
go through all that same stuff.

01:06:56.830 --> 01:06:57.830 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Stupid security.

01:06:57.830 --> 01:07:00.000 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Now, the guy
next to me is like, damn,

01:07:00.000 --> 01:07:01.000 align:middle line:90%
I go through this stuff.

01:07:01.000 --> 01:07:01.910 align:middle line:90%
I hate this stuff.

01:07:01.910 --> 01:07:05.210 align:middle line:84%
And it's like-- and the more
you hate it, the more, what?

01:07:05.210 --> 01:07:07.220 align:middle line:84%
Your brain is
releasing chemicals

01:07:07.220 --> 01:07:09.550 align:middle line:84%
that this is not
good, this is bad.

01:07:09.550 --> 01:07:12.709 align:middle line:84%
And the chemicals are not
going to make a good response.

01:07:12.709 --> 01:07:14.000 align:middle line:90%
If I sit in the same airplane--

01:07:14.000 --> 01:07:14.680 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Stress levels rise.

01:07:14.680 --> 01:07:16.400 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Their stress
level rises, OK?

01:07:16.400 --> 01:07:18.220 align:middle line:84%
I sit in the same
airplane and go, look,

01:07:18.220 --> 01:07:20.340 align:middle line:84%
I've done this so many times,
like, I'm not paying attention.

01:07:20.340 --> 01:07:20.840 align:middle line:90%
Why?

01:07:20.840 --> 01:07:23.070 align:middle line:84%
We go through this every
time so why should I

01:07:23.070 --> 01:07:24.790 align:middle line:90%
give it any more energy?

01:07:24.790 --> 01:07:26.640 align:middle line:90%
So I just disconnect.

01:07:26.640 --> 01:07:29.320 align:middle line:84%
I can sit there and think
of more wonderful things.

01:07:29.320 --> 01:07:32.200 align:middle line:84%
If I'm thinking of my partner,
Margaret, for example,

01:07:32.200 --> 01:07:33.960 align:middle line:84%
I'm not releasing
stress hormones.

01:07:33.960 --> 01:07:36.470 align:middle line:84%
I'm releasing a completely
different set of hormones.

01:07:36.470 --> 01:07:38.640 align:middle line:84%
In fact, if I could
illustrate it.

01:07:38.640 --> 01:07:39.140 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

01:07:39.140 --> 01:07:40.820 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: I like this.

01:07:40.820 --> 01:07:43.670 align:middle line:84%
My friend who creates
the covers of my books

01:07:43.670 --> 01:07:47.830 align:middle line:84%
took this idea for me and showed
that I'm a cell biologist, OK?

01:07:47.830 --> 01:07:48.352 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

01:07:48.352 --> 01:07:50.060 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: But all of
us, as individually,

01:07:50.060 --> 01:07:52.200 align:middle line:84%
we're controlling
our own cell cultures

01:07:52.200 --> 01:07:53.770 align:middle line:90%
that are inside our body.

01:07:53.770 --> 01:07:56.750 align:middle line:84%
So the brain is releasing
the chemicals that

01:07:56.750 --> 01:07:59.210 align:middle line:84%
create the cell culture
medium and, remember,

01:07:59.210 --> 01:08:00.940 align:middle line:84%
the environmental
medium controlled

01:08:00.940 --> 01:08:02.310 align:middle line:90%
the fate of the cells.

01:08:02.310 --> 01:08:05.070 align:middle line:84%
So while I'm a cell
biologist, all of us

01:08:05.070 --> 01:08:07.661 align:middle line:84%
personally are what we
would call self-biologists.

01:08:07.661 --> 01:08:09.035 align:middle line:84%
You're creating
your own biology.

01:08:09.035 --> 01:08:09.740 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's so interesting.

01:08:09.740 --> 01:08:10.320 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

01:08:10.320 --> 01:08:10.860 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

01:08:10.860 --> 01:08:12.776 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Now I say, OK,
so what does it mean?

01:08:12.776 --> 01:08:14.920 align:middle line:84%
It says when I
respond to the world,

01:08:14.920 --> 01:08:17.100 align:middle line:84%
my interpretation
causes neurochemicals

01:08:17.100 --> 01:08:18.930 align:middle line:84%
to be released by my
brain that correspond

01:08:18.930 --> 01:08:20.689 align:middle line:90%
with that interpretation.

01:08:20.689 --> 01:08:23.340 align:middle line:84%
Those chemicals are
then go into the blood.

01:08:23.340 --> 01:08:25.590 align:middle line:84%
And then that blood is
used to feed the cells.

01:08:25.590 --> 01:08:28.006 align:middle line:84%
So depending on the
chemistry of the blood,

01:08:28.006 --> 01:08:29.630 align:middle line:84%
it will organize the
fate of the cells.

01:08:29.630 --> 01:08:32.024 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So if it excretes
the hormone cortisol--

01:08:32.024 --> 01:08:32.649 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Yeah.

01:08:32.649 --> 01:08:33.470 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That's a
stress hormone, right?

01:08:33.470 --> 01:08:35.386 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: That's a totally
different response.

01:08:35.386 --> 01:08:38.700 align:middle line:84%
For example, let's say I open my
eyes and I see someone I love.

01:08:38.700 --> 01:08:39.500 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

01:08:39.500 --> 01:08:43.819 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: When I do that, I
release into my blood chemicals

01:08:43.819 --> 01:08:48.681 align:middle line:84%
from the brain such as dopamine,
oxytocin, vasopressin, growth

01:08:48.681 --> 01:08:49.180 align:middle line:90%
hormone.

01:08:49.180 --> 01:08:50.805 align:middle line:84%
These chemicals--
let me just tell you,

01:08:50.805 --> 01:08:53.229 align:middle line:84%
if I took those chemicals
released in love

01:08:53.229 --> 01:08:55.910 align:middle line:84%
and put it into a plastic
Petri dish with cells,

01:08:55.910 --> 01:08:58.450 align:middle line:84%
the cells would grow
exuberantly well.

01:08:58.450 --> 01:09:00.950 align:middle line:84%
And I think about it and I just
say, look, go back to a time

01:09:00.950 --> 01:09:03.939 align:middle line:84%
when you were really in a
state of exquisite love,

01:09:03.939 --> 01:09:05.040 align:middle line:90%
like a honeymoon.

01:09:05.040 --> 01:09:06.666 align:middle line:90%
And I say, were you healthy?

01:09:06.666 --> 01:09:09.040 align:middle line:84%
And most everybody goes, well,
I was exuberantly healthy.

01:09:09.040 --> 01:09:10.417 align:middle line:90%
And I go, well, you know why?

01:09:10.417 --> 01:09:12.000 align:middle line:84%
Because when you're
in a state of love

01:09:12.000 --> 01:09:13.979 align:middle line:84%
the chemistry you
release in the blood

01:09:13.979 --> 01:09:17.130 align:middle line:84%
is a chemistry that
encourages health and vitality

01:09:17.130 --> 01:09:18.826 align:middle line:90%
and energy in the system.

01:09:18.826 --> 01:09:19.950 align:middle line:90%
And I say, oh, that's cool.

01:09:19.950 --> 01:09:21.116 align:middle line:90%
And I say, well, wait, wait.

01:09:21.116 --> 01:09:23.010 align:middle line:84%
What if I open up my
eyes and I see something

01:09:23.010 --> 01:09:24.830 align:middle line:90%
that scares me so I'm in fear?

01:09:24.830 --> 01:09:26.060 align:middle line:90%
I go, oh.

01:09:26.060 --> 01:09:28.481 align:middle line:84%
The chemicals of love are
not going to released now.

01:09:28.481 --> 01:09:30.189 align:middle line:84%
Now you're going to
release the cortisol,

01:09:30.189 --> 01:09:32.022 align:middle line:84%
now you're going to
release stress hormones,

01:09:32.022 --> 01:09:34.069 align:middle line:90%
and cytokines, and histamines.

01:09:34.069 --> 01:09:37.840 align:middle line:84%
These elements get us ready
for fight or flight, OK?

01:09:37.840 --> 01:09:40.149 align:middle line:84%
Well, the relevance is
if I took those chemicals

01:09:40.149 --> 01:09:42.290 align:middle line:84%
and put it into a
plastic Petri dish,

01:09:42.290 --> 01:09:44.730 align:middle line:90%
it stops the growth of my cells.

01:09:44.730 --> 01:09:46.979 align:middle line:84%
And it does that because
it's going to conserve energy

01:09:46.979 --> 01:09:48.840 align:middle line:90%
for running, fight or flight.

01:09:48.840 --> 01:09:50.242 align:middle line:90%
So the point is this.

01:09:50.242 --> 01:09:51.950 align:middle line:84%
If you open your eyes
and you're in love,

01:09:51.950 --> 01:09:53.539 align:middle line:84%
you create a growth
medium that causes

01:09:53.539 --> 01:09:56.346 align:middle line:84%
the cells to be exuberantly
happy and healthy.

01:09:56.346 --> 01:09:57.720 align:middle line:84%
But if you open
your eyes and you

01:09:57.720 --> 01:10:00.270 align:middle line:84%
see something that stresses,
then all of a sudden

01:10:00.270 --> 01:10:02.340 align:middle line:84%
the chemistry
released by that is

01:10:02.340 --> 01:10:03.950 align:middle line:84%
chemistry that shuts
down the growth

01:10:03.950 --> 01:10:05.158 align:middle line:90%
and maintenance of the cells.

01:10:05.158 --> 01:10:06.200 align:middle line:90%
So guess what?

01:10:06.200 --> 01:10:08.420 align:middle line:90%
We know now for-- it's a fact.

01:10:08.420 --> 01:10:13.750 align:middle line:84%
90% of doctor visits are due to
stress, and the reason is why?

01:10:13.750 --> 01:10:17.127 align:middle line:84%
Because if you keep releasing
the stress hormones,

01:10:17.127 --> 01:10:19.085 align:middle line:84%
you keep shutting down
the growth of the cells.

01:10:19.085 --> 01:10:19.835 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That cell.

01:10:19.835 --> 01:10:23.220 align:middle line:84%
And it's also replicating in
terms of a destructed cell.

01:10:23.220 --> 01:10:24.080 align:middle line:90%
That cell is now--

01:10:24.080 --> 01:10:24.955 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Absolutely.

01:10:24.955 --> 01:10:28.250 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: -degenerating and
replicating degeneration

01:10:28.250 --> 01:10:30.470 align:middle line:84%
and then replicating
more degeneration.

01:10:30.470 --> 01:10:32.140 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Right, because the
signals that are released--

01:10:32.140 --> 01:10:33.180 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: -and that's
what you call cancer.

01:10:33.180 --> 01:10:34.805 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: The signals
that are released

01:10:34.805 --> 01:10:38.370 align:middle line:84%
are the signals that engage
inappropriate growth signals.

01:10:38.370 --> 01:10:40.870 align:middle line:84%
They're not for growth at
all, they're for protection.

01:10:40.870 --> 01:10:42.010 align:middle line:90%
And you have to look at it.

01:10:42.010 --> 01:10:45.400 align:middle line:84%
Growth and protection are
mutually opposite things,

01:10:45.400 --> 01:10:46.440 align:middle line:90%
and the reason is why?

01:10:46.440 --> 01:10:48.710 align:middle line:84%
Well, if a stimulus
causes growth,

01:10:48.710 --> 01:10:51.610 align:middle line:84%
it's something you move
to with your arms open.

01:10:51.610 --> 01:10:53.920 align:middle line:90%
Take it in, assimilate, grow.

01:10:53.920 --> 01:10:56.570 align:middle line:84%
But if there's a stimulus out
there that is threatening,

01:10:56.570 --> 01:10:58.890 align:middle line:84%
you don't move to
the stimulus, you

01:10:58.890 --> 01:11:00.230 align:middle line:90%
move away from the stimulus.

01:11:00.230 --> 01:11:03.130 align:middle line:84%
And not only that, but you
also close yourself down,

01:11:03.130 --> 01:11:04.400 align:middle line:90%
protection.

01:11:04.400 --> 01:11:05.560 align:middle line:90%
What's the point?

01:11:05.560 --> 01:11:07.970 align:middle line:90%
Growth is forward, open.

01:11:07.970 --> 01:11:10.150 align:middle line:90%
Protection is backwards, closed.

01:11:10.150 --> 01:11:12.030 align:middle line:84%
You can't do both of
them at the same time.

01:11:12.030 --> 01:11:16.450 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You can't be in growth
and in death at the same time,

01:11:16.450 --> 01:11:17.380 align:middle line:90%
essentially.

01:11:17.380 --> 01:11:18.385 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Exactly.

01:11:18.385 --> 01:11:21.980 align:middle line:84%
And yet, look at the world
we live in, 24/7, 365 stress.

01:11:21.980 --> 01:11:24.876 align:middle line:84%
The news, the economics,
all this stuff going on.

01:11:24.876 --> 01:11:25.750 align:middle line:90%
So what are we doing?

01:11:25.750 --> 01:11:29.080 align:middle line:84%
Every day we're taking the
growth medium called blood

01:11:29.080 --> 01:11:31.650 align:middle line:84%
and putting it into a chemistry
that actually shuts down

01:11:31.650 --> 01:11:33.450 align:middle line:90%
the maintenance of the system.

01:11:33.450 --> 01:11:37.370 align:middle line:84%
And the significance of that
is you cannot sustain stress.

01:11:37.370 --> 01:11:39.290 align:middle line:90%
Nature never intended that.

01:11:39.290 --> 01:11:41.960 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: For long periods
of time, that's true.

01:11:41.960 --> 01:11:44.677 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Nature was like, OK,
I'm being chased by a lion.

01:11:44.677 --> 01:11:46.760 align:middle line:84%
Now, I'm glad I got a
stress system because that's

01:11:46.760 --> 01:11:49.150 align:middle line:84%
going to let me run like hell
to get away from the lion.

01:11:49.150 --> 01:11:49.650 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

01:11:49.650 --> 01:11:52.108 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: But once I get away
from lion, it's like, oh, OK.

01:11:52.108 --> 01:11:53.905 align:middle line:84%
Things are good, and
I go back to growth.

01:11:53.905 --> 01:11:55.530 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And actually
there's a response

01:11:55.530 --> 01:11:57.655 align:middle line:84%
that happens there that
allows you to relax, right?

01:11:57.655 --> 01:11:58.610 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Absolutely.

01:11:58.610 --> 01:12:01.026 align:middle line:84%
But we don't have that in the
world that we live in today.

01:12:01.026 --> 01:12:03.220 align:middle line:84%
We are always running
from that lion.

01:12:03.220 --> 01:12:06.090 align:middle line:84%
Even our Darwinian Theory says
you better run from the lion

01:12:06.090 --> 01:12:08.590 align:middle line:84%
because it's a struggle
for your existence.

01:12:08.590 --> 01:12:11.480 align:middle line:84%
So we have built
in a belief that

01:12:11.480 --> 01:12:14.612 align:middle line:84%
even causes us to release
this kind of chemistry,

01:12:14.612 --> 01:12:15.820 align:middle line:90%
which is totally destructive.

01:12:15.820 --> 01:12:18.270 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So to chunk this
up into our human level,

01:12:18.270 --> 01:12:21.150 align:middle line:84%
if we're constantly in
survival for our jobs

01:12:21.150 --> 01:12:25.950 align:middle line:84%
and terrified of being fired,
or eating terrible food for us,

01:12:25.950 --> 01:12:28.865 align:middle line:84%
those are constant
stress responses?

01:12:28.865 --> 01:12:29.490 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Yeah.

01:12:29.490 --> 01:12:34.690 align:middle line:84%
Those are that-- the chemistry
of our blood to those stimuli

01:12:34.690 --> 01:12:36.270 align:middle line:84%
are not supportive
of growth at all.

01:12:36.270 --> 01:12:39.080 align:middle line:84%
In fact, they even shut
off the immune system.

01:12:39.080 --> 01:12:40.805 align:middle line:84%
So the more stress
you're under, not only

01:12:40.805 --> 01:12:43.500 align:middle line:84%
are you not feeding your cells
and keeping them healthy,

01:12:43.500 --> 01:12:45.930 align:middle line:84%
you're actually even
shutting off the protection

01:12:45.930 --> 01:12:49.022 align:middle line:84%
system inside the
body to-- actually,

01:12:49.022 --> 01:12:50.730 align:middle line:84%
the reason why is just
to conserve energy

01:12:50.730 --> 01:12:51.540 align:middle line:90%
for fight or flight.

01:12:51.540 --> 01:12:53.873 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But it's your perception
of that stress, though.

01:12:53.873 --> 01:12:56.430 align:middle line:84%
I remember when I interviewed
you many years ago

01:12:56.430 --> 01:12:59.860 align:middle line:84%
and I was a professional athlete
and I asked you at that time,

01:12:59.860 --> 01:13:02.130 align:middle line:84%
because I was training
very hard and I said,

01:13:02.130 --> 01:13:04.800 align:middle line:84%
does this level of
this vigorous exercise

01:13:04.800 --> 01:13:06.380 align:middle line:90%
put my body into stress?

01:13:06.380 --> 01:13:09.370 align:middle line:84%
And I specifically remember
you, on my radio show you said,

01:13:09.370 --> 01:13:10.597 align:middle line:90%
it's your perception of it.

01:13:10.597 --> 01:13:11.180 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Yes.

01:13:11.180 --> 01:13:12.010 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Can I tell
you something?

